# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: construction
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:construction/abn-amro] Following aggressive international expansion, ABN AMRO was acquired and broken up in 2007–2008 by a consortium of European banks, including Fortis which intended to take over its formed operations in the Benelux region.
[src:construction/abn-amro] Fortis came under stress in the autumn of 2008, and was in turn broken up into separate national entities; the Dutch operations, namely Fortis Bank Nederland and the former ABN AMRO activities that Fortis had planned to absorb, were nationalized, restructured, and renamed ABN AMRO in mid-2010.
[src:construction/abn-amro] On 20 November 2015, the Dutch government publicly re-listed the company through an IPO and sold 20 percent of the shares to the public.
[src:construction/abn-amro] ABN AMRO has been designated as a Significant Institution since the entry into force of European Banking Supervision in late 2014, and as a consequence is directly supervised by the European Central Bank.
[src:construction/abn-amro] In 1824, King William I established the Nederlandsche Handel-Maatschappij (NHM) a trading company to revive trade and financing of the Dutch East Indies and it would become one of the primary ancestors of ABN AMRO.
[src:construction/abn-amro] The NHM merged with the *Twentsche Bank* in 1964, to form Algemene Bank Nederland (ABN).
[src:construction/abn-amro] Also in 1964, the *Amsterdamsche Bank*, established in 1871, merged with the *Rotterdamsche Bank*, established in 1873 (as part of a merger that included *Determeijer Weslingh & Zn.* from 1765), to form Amsterdamsche en Rotterdamsche Bank, known as AMRO Bank.
[src:construction/abn-amro] On 22 September 1991, ABN and AMRO merged to form ABN AMRO.
[src:construction/abn-amro] In 1993, two of its investment banking subsidiaries ― Bank Mees & Hope and Pierson, Heldring & Pierson ― merged in turn to form MeesPierson.
[src:construction/abn-amro] The two merged banks brought to ABN AMRO a large network of overseas companies and branches.
[src:construction/abn-amro] From NHM, ABN owned a significant branch network in Asia and the Middle East, including the Saudi Hollandi Bank owned by the NHM Jeddah branch.
[src:construction/abn-amro] Another, the Hollandsche Bank-Unie (HBU), which grew from the merger of the *Hollandsche Bank voor de Middellandsche Zee* (HBMZ) and the *Hollandsche Zuid-Amerika Bank* in 1933, gave ABN AMRO an extensive network of branches in South and Central America.
[src:construction/abn-amro] In 1979, ABN had expanded into North America with the acquisition of Chicago-based LaSalle National Bank.
[src:construction/abn-amro] In 2005, Standard Federal became *LaSalle Bank Midwest* to unite ABN AMRO's two banking networks in the U.S.
[src:construction/abn-amro] In 1995, ABN AMRO purchased The Chicago Corporation, an American securities and commodities trading and clearing corporation.
[src:construction/abn-amro] Other major acquisitions included the Brazilian bank Banco Real in 1998, and the Italian bank Antonveneta in 2006.
[src:construction/abn-amro] It was also involved in the controversial acquisition of the Dutch local government mortgage and building development organisation, the Bouwfonds in 2000.
[src:construction/abn-amro] ABN AMRO sold the Bouwfonds as a going concern in 2006.
[src:construction/abn-amro] In July 2006, Favonius Ventures, which was founded and headed by Roel Pieper, received all of the technology investments of ABN AMRO Capital which is the private equity business unit of ABN AMRO Bank N.V.
[src:construction/abn-amro] ABN AMRO had come to a crossroads in early 2005.
[src:construction/abn-amro] The bank had still not come close to its own target of having a return on equity that would put it among the top five of its peer group, a target that the CEO, Rijkman Groenink had set upon his appointment in 2000.
[src:construction/abn-amro] From 2000 until 2005, ABN AMRO's stock price stagnated.
[src:construction/abn-amro] Financial results in 2006 added to concerns about the bank's future.
[src:construction/abn-amro] Operating expenses increased at a greater rate than operating revenue, and the efficiency ratio deteriorated further to 69.9%.
[src:construction/abn-amro] Non-performing loans increased considerably year on year by 192%.
[src:construction/abn-amro] Net profits were only boosted by sustained asset sales.
[src:construction/abn-amro] In 2006, research findings were publicly released regarding ABN AMRO Bank N.V.'s predecessors and connections to African slavery.
[src:construction/abn-amro] An examination of 200 predecessors of ABN AMRO Bank N.V. founded before 1888 determined that some had connections to African slavery, either in the United States or elsewhere in the Americas.
[src:construction/abn-amro] By 2007, ABN AMRO was the second-largest bank in the Netherlands and the eighth-largest in Europe by assets.
[src:construction/abn-amro] At that time, the magazine *The Banker* and Fortune Global 500 placed it 15th in the list of world's biggest banks and it had operations in 63 countries, with over 110,000 employees.
[src:construction/abn-amro] Pakistan merged with Prime Commercial Bank which consisted of 69 branches across 24 cities.
[src:construction/abn-amro] ABN AMRO Bank (Pakistan) Limited (Which later got merged into Royal Bank of Scotland Pakistan) was formed as the result of the US$227 million acquisition.
[src:construction/abn-amro] On 21 February 2007, The Children's Investment Fund Management (TCI) hedge fund called to ask the Chairman of the Supervisory Board to actively investigate a merger, acquisition, or breakup of ABN AMRO, stating that the current stock price did not reflect the true value of the underlying assets.
[src:construction/abn-amro] TCI asked the chairman to put its request on the agenda of the annual shareholders' meeting to be held in April 2007.
[src:construction/abn-amro] Events accelerated on 20 March 2007, when the British bank Barclays and ABN AMRO both confirmed they were in exclusive talks about a possible merger.
[src:construction/abn-amro] On 28 March 2007, ABN AMRO published the agenda for the shareholders' meeting of 2007.
[src:construction/abn-amro] It included all items requested by TCI, but with the recommendation not to follow the request for a breakup of the company.
[src:construction/abn-amro] According to the proposed deal, RBS would receive ABN's United States operations, LaSalle, and ABN's wholesale operations; Banco Santander would take the Brazilian operations; and Fortis, the Dutch operations.
[src:construction/abn-amro] The three banks set up a joint venture, RFS Holdings (with a name based on their respective initials), to execute the transaction.
[src:construction/abn-amro] On 23 April, ABN AMRO and Barclays announced the proposed acquisition of ABN AMRO by Barclays.
[src:construction/abn-amro] The deal was valued at €67 billion and included the sale of LaSalle Bank to Bank of America for €21 billion.
[src:construction/abn-amro] Two days later, the RBS-led consortium brought out its indicative offer, worth €72 billion, if ABN AMRO would abandon its sale of LaSalle Bank to Bank of America.
[src:construction/abn-amro] During the shareholders' meeting the next day, approximately 68 percent of the shareholders voted in favor of the breakup as requested by TCI.
[src:construction/abn-amro] The sale of LaSalle was seen as obstructive by many: as a way of blocking the RBS bid, which hinged on further access to the US markets, in order to expand on the success of the group's existing American brands, Citizens Bank and Charter One.
[src:construction/abn-amro] On 3 May 2007, the Dutch Investors' Association (Vereniging van Effectenbezitters), with the support of shareholders representing up to 20 percent of ABN's shares, took its case to the Dutch commercial court in Amsterdam, seeking an injunction against the LaSalle sale.
[src:construction/abn-amro] The court ruled that the sale of LaSalle could not be viewed apart from the current merger talks of Barclays with ABN AMRO and that the ABN AMRO shareholders should be able to approve other possible merger/acquisition candidates in a general shareholder meeting.
[src:construction/abn-amro] However, in July 2007, the Dutch Supreme Court ruled that Bank of America's acquisition of LaSalle Bank could proceed and Bank of America absorbed LaSalle effective 1 October 2007.
[src:construction/abn-amro] On 23 July 2007, Barclays raised its offer for ABN AMRO to €67.5bn, after securing investments from the governments of China and Singapore, but it was still short of the RBS consortium's offer.
[src:construction/abn-amro] Barclay's revised bid was worth €35.73 a share — 4.3% more than its previous offer.
[src:construction/abn-amro] The offer, which included 37% cash, remained below the €38.40-a-share offer made the week before by the RFS consortium.
[src:construction/abn-amro] The revised offer did not include an offer for La Salle Bank since ABN AMRO could proceed with the sale of that subsidiary to Bank of America.
[src:construction/abn-amro] RBS would now settle for ABN's investment-banking division and its Asian Network.
[src:construction/abn-amro] On 30 July 2007, ABN AMRO withdrew its support for Barclays' offer which was lower than the offer from the group led by RBS.
[src:construction/abn-amro] While the Barclays offer matched ABN AMRO's "strategic vision," the board couldn't recommend it from "a financial point of view." The US$98.3bn bid from RBS, Fortis, and Banco Santander was 9.8% higher than Barclays' offer.
[src:construction/abn-amro] Barclays Bank withdrew its bid for ABN AMRO on 5 October, clearing the way for the RBS-led consortium's bid to go through, along with its planned dismemberment of ABN AMRO.
[src:construction/abn-amro] RFS formally acquired ABN AMRO on 17 October 2007.
[src:construction/abn-amro] Fortis would receive ABN AMRO's Dutch and Belgian operations, Banco Santander would get Banco Real in Brazil, and Banca Antonveneta in Italy and RBS would get ABN AMRO's wholesale division and all other operations, including those in Asia.
[src:construction/abn-amro] Both RBS and Fortis were increasingly visibly overextended following the ABN AMRO acquisition.
[src:construction/abn-amro] On 22 April 2008, RBS announced the largest rights issue in British corporate history, which aimed to raise £12billion in new capital to offset a writedown of £5.9billion resulting from the bad investments and to shore up its reserves following the purchase of ABN AMRO.
[src:construction/abn-amro] On 11 July 2008, Fortis CEO Jean Votron stepped down after the ABN AMRO deal had depleted Fortis's capital.
[src:construction/abn-amro] The total worth of Fortis, as reflected by its stock value, was at that time one-third of what it had been before the acquisition, and just under the value it had paid for the Benelux activities of ABN AMRO.
[src:construction/abn-amro] On 3 October 2008, Fortis was nationalised.
[src:construction/abn-amro] The Dutch government bought a number of Fortis divisions plus Fortis's share in ABN AMRO for EUR 16.8 billion.
[src:construction/abn-amro] It subsequently announced that the parts of ABN AMRO it had acquired would be integrated with Fortis Bank Nederland (FBN) to create a new ABN AMRO.
[src:construction/abn-amro] On 13 October 2008, British Prime Minister Gordon Brown announced a UK government bailout of the financial system.
[src:construction/abn-amro] The Treasury would infuse £37 billion ($64 billion, €47 billion) of new capital into Royal Bank of Scotland Group Plc, Lloyds TSB and HBOS Plc, to avert financial sector collapse.
[src:construction/abn-amro] This resulted in a total government ownership in RBS of 58%.
[src:construction/abn-amro] As a consequence of this rescue, the chief executive of the group Fred Goodwin offered his resignation, which was duly accepted.
[src:construction/abn-amro] Later in October, Fortis announced that it would sell its stake in RFS Holdings, which included all activities that had not been transferred yet to Fortis (i.e. everything except asset management).
[src:construction/abn-amro] In September 2009, RBS rebranded the Morgans sharedealing business in Australia as RBS Morgans.
[src:construction/abn-amro] This followed the rebranding of the ABN AMRO Australia unit to RBS Australia in March that year.
[src:construction/abn-amro] On 10 February 2010, RBS announced that branches it owned in India and the United Arab Emirates were to be rebranded under its name.
[src:construction/abn-amro] HSBC Holdings said it would buy the Indian retail and commercial banking businesses of Royal Bank of Scotland for $1.8bn, however the deal fell-through in December 2012.
[src:construction/abn-amro] The operations owned by Santander, notably those in Italy and Brazil, were merged with Santander, sold or eliminated.
[src:construction/abn-amro] The Dutch government had obtained full control of all Fortis operations in the Netherlands, including those parts of ABN-AMRO then belonging to Fortis, at a price of €16.8bn.
[src:construction/abn-amro] The government and the De Nederlandsche Bank president have announced the merger of Dutch Fortis and ABN AMRO parts will proceed while the bank is in state ownership.
[src:construction/abn-amro] This was completed in July 2010, when Fortis operations in the Netherlands were rebranded ABN AMRO.
[src:construction/abn-amro] In November 2008, a Belgian court dismissed a suit by shareholders of Fortis objecting to the Belgian government's handling of the Fortis/ABN AMRO transaction and subsequent break-up.
[src:construction/abn-amro] The Dutch government appointed former Dutch finance minister Gerrit Zalm as CEO to restructure and stabilise the bank, and in February 2010 the assets it owned were legally demerged from those owned by RBS.
[src:construction/abn-amro] This demerger created two separate organisations, ABN AMRO Bank N.V. and The Royal Bank of Scotland N.V.
[src:construction/abn-amro] The former was merged with ABN AMRO Private Banking, Fortis Bank Nederland, the private bank MeesPierson (formerly owned by the original ABN AMRO and Fortis) and the diamond bank International Diamond & Jewelry Group to create ABN AMRO Group N.V., with the Fortis name being dropped on 1 July 2010.
[src:construction/abn-amro] The remaining parts of the original ABN AMRO still owned by The Royal Bank of Scotland N.V., meanwhile, were renamed, sold or closed.
[src:construction/abn-amro] As part of the agreement with the European Commission on state aid in the restructuring, ABN AMRO sold Hollandsche Bank-Unie to Deutsche Bank in April 2010, together with another subsidiary, IFN Finance.
[src:construction/abn-amro] ABN AMRO acquired the specialist on-line mortgage provider *Direktbank Hypotheken* as part of the nationalisation and from 1 January 2011, it stopped selling these products under this brand to the public.
[src:construction/abn-amro] It absorbed the mortgage business into its own products under the ABN AMRO brand as well as Florius brand.
[src:construction/abn-amro] In November 2020, ABN AMRO announced it would cut 2800 jobs and sell its head offices as a plan to reduce costs, hoping to save €700 million by 2024.
[src:construction/abn-amro] In December 2023, ABN AMRO acquired BUX to boost its digital presence for an undisclosed amount.
[src:construction/abn-amro] In May 2024, ABN AMRO agreed to buy Hauck Aufhäuser Lampe (HAL), a German private bank specialised in wealth management, for 672 million euros ($730 million) from Chinese conglomerate Fosun International.
[src:construction/abn-amro] In October 2024, the Dutch government announced its plan to reduce its stake in ABN AMRO from 40.5% to 30% in the coming months.
[src:construction/abn-amro] On 12 November 2025, ABN AMRO announced the acquisition of Dutch lender NIBC Bank for 960 million euros from American private equity firm Blackstone.
[src:construction/abn-amro] ABN AMRO Bank has offices in 15 countries with 32,000 employees, most of whom are based in the Netherlands with only 5,000 in other countries.
[src:construction/abn-amro] Its operations include a private banking division which focuses on high-net-worth clients in 14 countries as well as commercial and merchant banking operations that play a major role in energy, commodities and transportation markets as well as brokerage, clearing, and custody.
[src:construction/abn-amro] In April 2022, ABN AMRO Bank announced the company had signed a multi-year subscription extension with Switzerland based Banking and financial software development organisation Temenos.
[src:construction/abn-amro] The deal was made to support ABN AMRO with customer growth and overall business expansion on the Temenos Banking cloud.
[src:construction/abn-amro] The bank refers to itself as ABN AMRO in all capitals, based on an acronym of the two originating banks names Algemene Bank Nederland and the Amsterdam and Rotterdam Bank, in the second case the first two letters of each city make up the word AMRO.
[src:construction/abn-amro] The letters in 'ABN' are pronounced separately and 'AMRO' is pronounced as a word.
[src:construction/abn-amro] For this reason some media spell the name as 'ABN Amro'.
[src:construction/abn-amro] In written text both versions are used, although the bank itself uses only the uppercase version.
[src:construction/abn-amro] In conversations, the bank is sometimes referred to as simply ABN or AMRO bank depending on one's location around the world.
[src:construction/abn-amro] The green and yellow shield logo was designed by Landor Associates for ABN AMRO in 1991, and has been used as a brand for the bank and all its subsidiaries.
[src:construction/abn-amro] ABN AMRO was the main sponsor of Dutch football club AFC Ajax of Amsterdam from 1991 to 2008.
[src:construction/abn-amro] The sponsor logo was at the time the only one in the world to be printed vertically down the right hand side of the front of the shirt.
[src:construction/abn-amro] As of 2014, ABN AMRO is one of the strategic industry partners with Duisenberg School of Finance.
[src:construction/abn-amro] The bank's former art collection has been managed since the end of 2007 by a dedicated foundation, the Stichting ABN AMRO Kunstverzameling.
[src:construction/abn-amro] As a result of the alleged fraud by Bernard Madoff, Fortis Bank Netherlands (Holding) NV lost 1 billion euros on loans from the bank (through its subsidiary Prime Fund Solutions, part of Fortis Merchant Banking) to hedge fund and as collateral investments in Bernard Madoff Investment Securities.
[src:construction/abn-amro] The Dutch government said on behalf of Fortis that a claim against the Securities and Exchange Commission would be considered.
[src:construction/abn-amro] ABN AMRO was mentioned by the United States Securities and Exchange Commission (SEC) in court filings when it sued Goldman Sachs and one of Goldman's collateralized debt obligation (CDO) traders on 16 April 2010.
[src:construction/abn-amro] The SEC alleges that Goldman defrauded both IKB Deutsche Industriebank and ABN AMRO by its failure to disclose that the CDOs it sold to both banks were not assembled by a third party, but instead through the guidance of a hedge fund that was counterparty in the CDS transaction.
[src:construction/abn-amro] This hedge fund, Paulson & Co., stood to reap great financial benefit in the event of default.
[src:construction/abn-amro] ABN AMRO bank is one of the main banks financing the diamond business.
[src:construction/abn-amro] ABN AMRO had branches in Botswana, New York, Hong Kong, Mumbai and Dubai, all of which they have sold or are in process of closing.
[src:construction/abn-amro] They currently only have a branch in Antwerp, where they are also shrinking their business.
[src:construction/accountant] An **accountant** is a practitioner of accounting or accountancy.
[src:construction/accountant] Accountants who have demonstrated competency through their professional associations' certification exams are certified to use titles such as Chartered Accountant, Chartered Certified Accountant or Certified Public Accountant, or Registered Public Accountant.
[src:construction/accountant] Such professionals are granted certain responsibilities by statute, such as the ability to certify an organization's financial statements, and may be held liable for professional misconduct.
[src:construction/accountant] Non-qualified accountants may be employed by a qualified accountant, or may work independently without statutory privileges and obligations.
[src:construction/accountant] Cahan & Sun (2015) used archival study to determine whether accountants' personal characteristics may exert a very significant impact during the audit process and further influence audit fees and audit quality.
[src:construction/accountant] Practitioners have been portrayed in popular culture by the stereotype of the humorless, introspective bean-counter.
[src:construction/accountant] It has been suggested that the stereotype has an influence on those attracted to the profession with many new entrants underestimating the importance of communication skills and overestimating the importance of numeracy in the role.
[src:construction/accountant] An accountant may either be hired for a firm that requires accounting services on a continuous basis, or may belong to an accounting firm that provides accounting consulting services to other firms.
[src:construction/accountant] The Big Four auditors are the largest employers of accountants worldwide.
[src:construction/accountant] However, most accountants are employed in commerce, industry, and the public sector.
[src:construction/accountant] The Institute of Chartered Accountants of Scotland (ICAS) received its Royal Charter in 1854 and is the world's first professional body of accountants.
[src:construction/accountant] Unlike a 'Chartered Accountant', the title 'accountant' does not require a specific qualification or licence in the UK, meaning anyone can call themselves an 'accountant'.
[src:construction/accountant] HMRC's research suggests that one third of practising accountants do not belong to any professional body.
[src:construction/accountant] Excepting the Association of Certified Public Accountants, each of the above bodies admits members only after passing examinations and undergoing a period of relevant work experience.
[src:construction/accountant] Once admitted, members are expected to comply with ethical guidelines and gain appropriate professional experience.
[src:construction/accountant] The ICAEW, ICAS, ICAI, ACCA and AAPA are five Recognised Supervisory Bodies (**RSB**) in the UK.
[src:construction/accountant] A member of one of them may also become a *Statutory Auditor* in accordance with the Companies Act, providing they can demonstrate the necessary professional ability in that area and submit to regular inspection.
[src:construction/accountant] It is illegal for any individual or firm that is not a Statutory Auditor to perform a company audit.
[src:construction/accountant] The ICAEW, ICAS, ICAI, ACCA, AIA and CIPFA are six recognised qualifying bodies statutory (**RQB**) in the UK.
[src:construction/accountant] A member of one of them may also become a *Statutory Auditor* in accordance with the Companies Act, providing they are a member of one of the five Recognised Supervisory Bodies **RSB** mentioned above.
[src:construction/accountant] All six RQBs are listed under EU mutual recognition directives to practise in 27 EU member states and individually entered into agreement with the Hong Kong Institute of Certified Public Accountants (HKICPA).
[src:construction/accountant] Further restrictions apply to accountants who carry out insolvency work.
[src:construction/accountant] In addition to the bodies above, technical qualifications are offered by the Association of Accounting Technicians, ACCA and AIA, which are respectively called AAT Technician, CAT (Certified Accounting Technician) and IAT (International Accounting Technician).
[src:construction/accountant] In the United States, licensed accountants are Certified Public Accountants (CPAs), and in certain states, Public Accountants (PAs).
[src:construction/accountant] Unlicensed accountants may be Certified Internal Auditors (CIAs) and Certified Management Accountants (CMAs).
[src:construction/accountant] The difference between these certifications is primarily the legal status and the types of services provided, although individuals may earn more than one certification.
[src:construction/accountant] Additionally, much accounting work is performed by uncertified individuals, who may be working under the supervision of a certified accountant.
[src:construction/accountant] As noted above, the majority of accountants work in the private sector or may offer their services without the need for certification.
[src:construction/accountant] A CPA is licensed by a state to provide auditing services to the public.
[src:construction/accountant] Many CPA firms also offer accounting, tax, litigation support, and other financial advisory services.
[src:construction/accountant] The requirements for receiving the CPA license vary from state to state, although the passage of the Uniform Certified Public Accountant Examination is required by all states.
[src:construction/accountant] This examination is designed and graded by the American Institute of Certified Public Accountants (AICPA).
[src:construction/accountant] A PA (sometimes referred to as LPA—Licensed Public Accountant) is licensed by the state to practice accountancy to the same extent as are CPAs, although in some states PAs are not permitted to perform audits or reviews (notably Iowa, Minnesota, Oregon, & South Carolina).
[src:construction/accountant] A PA's ability to practice out of state is very limited due to most states having phased out the PA designation.
[src:construction/accountant] While most states no longer accept new PA license applicants, four states still accept PA applicants for practice privileges within the state.
[src:construction/accountant] As with the CPA, the requirements for receiving the PA license vary from state to state.
[src:construction/accountant] Most states require a passage of either two or three (out of four) sections of the CPA exam or passage of the Comprehensive Examination for Accreditation in Accounting which is administered and graded by the Accreditation Council for Accountancy and Taxation (ACAT).
[src:construction/accountant] A certified internal auditor (CIA) is granted a certificate from the Institute of Internal Auditors (IIA), provided that the candidate has passed a four-part examination.
[src:construction/accountant] One of the four parts is waived if the candidate has already passed the CPA Exam.
[src:construction/accountant] A CIA typically provides services directly to an employer rather than to the public.
[src:construction/accountant] A person holding the Certificate in Management Accounting (CMA) is granted the certificate by the Institute of Management Accountants (IMA), provided that the candidate has passed an examination of two parts and has met the practical experience requirement of the IMA.
[src:construction/accountant] A CMA provides services directly to employers rather than to the public.
[src:construction/accountant] A CMA can also provide services to the public, but to an extent much lesser than that of a CPA.
[src:construction/accountant] An Enrolled Agent (EA) is a federally authorized tax practitioner empowered by the U.S.
[src:construction/accountant] Department of the Treasury to represent taxpayers before the Internal Revenue Service (IRS).
[src:construction/accountant] Enrolled agent status is the highest credential awarded by the IRS, unlimited rights of representation.
[src:construction/accountant] The EA credential is recognized across all 50 U.S. states.
[src:construction/accountant] Candidates must pass a three-part exam (called the Special Enrollment Examination) covering the subjects of individual tax, business tax, and client representation, or must have worked at the IRS for five consecutive years in a position which regularly engaged in these areas.
[src:construction/accountant] The United States Department of Labor's Bureau of Labor Statistics estimates that there are about one million persons employed as accountants and auditors in the U.S.
[src:construction/accountant] U.S. tax laws grant CPAs and EAs a form of accountant–client privilege.
[src:construction/accountant] In Australia, there are three legally recognised local professional accounting bodies which all enjoy the same recognition and can be considered as "qualified accountant": the Institute of Public Accountants (IPA), CPA Australia (CPA) and the Chartered Accountants Australia and New Zealand (CAANZ).
[src:construction/accountant] Other international bodies such as ACCA (The Association of Chartered Certified Accountants) and Institute of Chartered Accountants in England and Wales (ICAEW) enjoy recognition for the purposes of supporting their members in their careers.
[src:construction/accountant] For instance, ACCA has achieved recognition by the Tax Practitioner Board, as Tax and BAS agents, in 2010.
[src:construction/accountant] In Canada, a **Chartered Professional Accountant (CPA)** must be a member of the Chartered Professional Accountants of Canada (designatory letters CPA).
[src:construction/accountant] Up to 2013, there were three nationally recognized accounting designations in Canada: Chartered Accountant (CA), Certified General Accountant (CGA), and Certified Management Accountants (CMA).
[src:construction/accountant] The national CA and CGA bodies were created by Acts of Parliament in 1902 and 1913 respectively, The national CMA organization was established under the Canada Corporations Act in 1920.
[src:construction/accountant] Chartered Professional Accountants of Canada (CPA Canada) was established by CICA and CMA Canada on January 1, 2013, under the Canada Not-for-profit Corporations Act, to support Canadian provincial accounting bodies that were unifying under the CPA banner.
[src:construction/accountant] CGA-Canada integrated with CPA Canada on October 1, 2014, completing the unification of Canada's accounting profession at the national level.
[src:construction/accountant] All recognized national and provincial accounting bodies in Canada have now unified under the CPA banner.
[src:construction/accountant] The Canadian CPA designation is held by more than 200,000 members in Canada and around the world.
[src:construction/accountant] In Japan, a certified public accountant must be a member of the Japanese Institute of Certified Public Accountants (JICPA).
[src:construction/accountant] It is the sole professional accountancy organization in Japan.
[src:construction/accountant] Chartered accountancy is offered in India by the Institute of Chartered Accountants of India (ICAI), the second largest accounting body in the world.
[src:construction/accountant] This Institute was established in 1949 under the Chartered Accountants Act, 1949 for the regulation of the profession of chartered accountants in India.
[src:construction/accountant] The ICAI set up the Accountancy Museum of India in 2009, the third museum of accounting in the world.
[src:construction/accountant] The members of the Institute are widely recognized as Cost and Management Accountants (FCMA, ACMA).
[src:construction/accountant] Under Public Accountants Law ( UU 5/2011), the Institute of Certified Public Accountants of Indonesia (IAPI) is the professional organization having the authority to issue CPA designation which is the statutory requirements for obtaining public accountant license from the government.
[src:construction/accountant] The Institute of Chartered Accountants of Pakistan (ICAP) offers chartered accountant studies in Pakistan.
[src:construction/accountant] ICAP was established under The Chartered Accountants Ordinance, 1961 as a self-regulatory body.
[src:construction/accountant] The Institute of Cost and Management Accountants of Pakistan (ICMAP) offers accountant studies in Pakistan.
[src:construction/accountant] ICMAP was established under The Cost and Management Accountants Act, 1966.
[src:construction/accountant] Pakistan Institute of Public Finance Accountants (PIPFA) is an autonomous body recognized mainly in the government sector and established under license from the Securities and Exchange Commission of Pakistan by the authority given under section 42 of the Companies Ordinance, 1984.
[src:construction/accountant] The body is co-sponsored by the Institute of Chartered Accountants of Pakistan, the Institute of Cost and Management Accountants of Pakistan and the Auditor General of Pakistan.PIPFA has more than 5,000 members and a number of them are members of ICAP and ICMAP.
[src:construction/accountant] Chartered accountancy is governed in Bangladesh by the Institute of Chartered Accountants of Bangladesh (ICAB).
[src:construction/accountant] In New Zealand, there are two local accountancy bodies the Chartered Accountants Australia and New Zealand (CAANZ) and the New Zealand Association of Certified Public Accountants (NZACPA) the operating name of New Zealand Association of Accountants Inc (NZAA).
[src:construction/accountant] To audit public companies an individual must be a member of either the CAANZ or an otherwise gazetted body.
[src:construction/accountant] Chartered Certified Accountant (Association of Chartered Certified Accountants or FCCA) qualification has also been gazetted under.
[src:construction/accountant] An ACCA member can practice as long as they hold an ACCA public practice certificate (with audit qualification) in their country of origin.
[src:construction/accountant] In Singapore, a public accountant must be a member of any professional accountancy body in Singapore.
[src:construction/accountant] Institute of Singapore Chartered Accountants (ISCA) is the sole local accountancy body, therefore the public accountant must be a member of the ISCA.
[src:construction/accountant] In Sri Lanka, a chartered accountant must be a member of the Institute of Chartered Accountants of Sri Lanka (designatory letters ACA or FCA).
[src:construction/accountant] It is the sole local accountancy body, therefore to audit public companies an individual must be a member of the ICASL.
[src:construction/accountant] A Certified management account also must be a member of the Institute of Management Accountants of Sri Lanka (designatory letters ACMA or FCMA).
[src:construction/accountant] In Austria, the accountancy profession is regulated by the Bilanzbuchhaltungsgesetz 2006 (BibuG – Management Accountancy Law).
[src:construction/accountant] In Hong Kong, the accountancy industry is regulated by Hong Kong Institute of Certified Public Accountants(HKICPA) under the Professional Accountants Ordinance (Chapter 50, Laws of Hong Kong).
[src:construction/accountant] The auditing industry for limited companies is regulated under the Companies Ordinance (Chapter 32, Laws of Hong Kong), and other ordinances such as the securities and futures ordinance, the listing rules, etc.
[src:construction/accountant] HKICPA terminated all recognition of overshare bodies in 2005 for *accreditation* under professional accountants ordinance.
[src:construction/accountant] In general, all British RQBs except for CIPFA were re-accredited.
[src:construction/accountant] Please refer to HKICPA for latest recognition.
[src:construction/accountant] In Portugal, there are two accountancy qualifications: the *Contabilistas Certificados* (CC), responsible for producing accounting and tax information, and the *Revisor Oficial de Contas* (ROC), more related to auditing practices.
[src:construction/accountant] The CC certification is exclusively awarded by the professional organization *Ordem dos Contabilistas Certificados* (OCC), and the certification to become an auditor is awarded by another professional organization, the *Ordem dos Revisores Oficiais de Contas* (OROC).
[src:construction/accountant] In general, accountants or auditors accredited by OTOC or OROC are individuals with university graduation diplomas in business management, economics, mathematics or law who, after further studies, applied for an exam and received the certification to be a CC or ROC.
[src:construction/accountant] That certification is only received after a one-year (CC) or three-year (ROC) internship.
[src:construction/accountant] Any citizen having a polytechnic degree as a bookkeeper is also entitled to apply for the exam and certification at the OCC.
[src:construction/agile-construction] Like the Toyota Production System, agile construction principles form a system that relies on input from the source of the work information, both up front for planning the project, as well as throughout the life of a project for real-time feedback.
[src:construction/agile-construction] The real-time input produces real-time measurements of productivity and allows for improved responsiveness to changes on the jobsite.
[src:construction/agile-construction] Iterative and incremental agile construction methods help manage the design and build of efficient, low-risk processes and activities.
[src:construction/agile-construction] This means that each time a process is repeated some changes are made to improve the process.
[src:construction/agile-construction] Changes for the better are kept and for the worse are discarded.
[src:construction/agile-construction] Agile construction principles help contractors to make processes visible, measurable and manageable to improve the ability to rapidly adapt to job site changes, by minimizing the time between when a risk is detected and when it gets corrected.
[src:construction/agile-construction] This requires a better mechanism to predict and capture these changes accompanied with a better infrastructure for addressing them.
[src:construction/agile-construction] Agile Construction project management can also make gains in pre-design and design phases of construction projects.
[src:construction/agile-construction] Accompanied with a well-trained and highly motivated workforce, companies using agile construction operations are able to increase responsiveness and productivity, to reduce cost and to deliver a better customer value.
[src:construction/air-traffic-obstacle] An **Air traffic obstacle** is a tall structure which can endanger air traffic.
[src:construction/air-traffic-obstacle] Air traffic obstacles have to be marked in most cases with red and white colored markings and with aircraft warning lights at night.
[src:construction/air-traffic-obstacle] On larger structures blinking lights are required.
[src:construction/air-traffic-obstacle] An example of an air traffic obstacle is the air traffic control tower.
[src:construction/air-traffic-obstacle] In the past lamps similar to those used on lighthouses were sometimes used.
[src:construction/air-traffic-obstacle] There are still such lamps on Fernsehturm Stuttgart in Stuttgart, Germany.
[src:construction/air-traffic-obstacle] A fainter rotating light is on Blosenbergturm, Beromünster, Switzerland.
[src:construction/air-traffic-obstacle] A special method of marking was used at the mast of Deutschlandsender Herzberg/Elster in 1939.
[src:construction/air-traffic-obstacle] On small poles near the mast multiple rotating skybeamers were mounted which illuminated the lens-like structure on the top.
[src:construction/air-traffic-obstacle] Because of this no electrical installation was required on this mast.
[src:construction/al-gamil] Al Gamil is the largest construction firm in Djibouti.
[src:construction/al-gamil] It has its headquarters in the national capital, Djibouti City.
[src:construction/al-gamil] Besides the local construction industry, the Al-Gamil Group (Groupe Al Gamil) also imports and exports various commodities.
[src:construction/al-gamil] Among these products for the domestic and international markets are construction materials, foodstuffs and vehicles.
[src:construction/al-gamil] The company is a member of the Club Echanges Normandie Afrique.
[src:construction/al-gamil] It has additional offices in Dubai and Sharjah in the United Arab Emirates.
[src:construction/american-institute-of-constructors] The **American Institute of Constructors** (**AIC**), is a not-for-profit 501(c)(6) non-governmental professional association founded in 1971.
[src:construction/american-institute-of-constructors] Individuals involved in the AIC are typically found in the construction management Industry.
[src:construction/american-institute-of-constructors] The AIC offers three different levels of certification: Associate Constructor (AC), Certified Professional Constructor (CPC), and Fellow (FC).
[src:construction/american-institute-of-constructors] American Institute of Constructors also offers a number of educational programs, including online courses, webinars, and in-person seminars.
[src:construction/american-society-of-civil-engineers] The **American Society of Civil Engineers** (**ASCE**) is a tax-exempt professional body founded in 1852 to represent members of the civil engineering profession worldwide.
[src:construction/american-society-of-civil-engineers] Headquartered in Reston, Virginia, it is the oldest national engineering society in the United States.
[src:construction/american-society-of-civil-engineers] Its constitution was based on the older Boston Society of Civil Engineers from 1848.
[src:construction/american-society-of-civil-engineers] ASCE is dedicated to the advancement of the science and profession of civil engineering and the enhancement of human welfare through the activities of society members.
[src:construction/american-society-of-civil-engineers] It has more than 143,000 members in 177 countries.
[src:construction/american-society-of-civil-engineers] Its mission is to provide essential value to members, their careers, partners, and the public; facilitate the advancement of technology; encourage and provide the tools for lifelong learning; promote professionalism and the profession; develop and support civil engineers.
[src:construction/american-society-of-civil-engineers] The first serious and documented attempts to organize civil engineers as a professional society in the newly created United States were in the early 19th century.
[src:construction/american-society-of-civil-engineers] Later, in 1834, an American trade periodical, the "American Railroad Journal," advocated for a similar national organization of civil engineers.
[src:construction/american-society-of-civil-engineers] On December 17, 1838, a petition started circulating asking civil engineers to meet in 1839 in Baltimore, Maryland, to organize a permanent society of civil engineers.
[src:construction/american-society-of-civil-engineers] Prior to that, thirteen notable civil engineers largely identifiable as being from New York, Pennsylvania, or Maryland met in Philadelphia.
[src:construction/american-society-of-civil-engineers] Forty engineers actually appeared at the February 1839 meeting in Baltimore, including J.
[src:construction/american-society-of-civil-engineers] Edgar Thomson (Future Chief Engineer and later President of the Pennsylvania Railroad), Wright, Roberts, Edward Miller, and the Maryland engineers Isaac Trimble and Benjamin Henry Latrobe II and attendees from as far as Massachusetts, Illinois, and Louisiana.
[src:construction/american-society-of-civil-engineers] Miller later ascribed the failure to the difficulties of assembling members due to available means for traveling in the country at the time.
[src:construction/american-society-of-civil-engineers] That journal continued discussion on forming an engineers' organization from 1839 thru 1843 serving its own self-interests in advocating its journal as a replacement for a professional society but to no avail.
[src:construction/american-society-of-civil-engineers] During the 1840s, professional organizations continued to develop and organize in the United States.
[src:construction/american-society-of-civil-engineers] During this same period of association incorporations in the 1840s, attempts were again made at organizing an American engineer association.
[src:construction/american-society-of-civil-engineers] They succeeded at first with the Boston Society of Civil Engineers, organized in 1848, and then in October 1852, with an effort to organize a Society of Civil Engineers and Architects in New York.
[src:construction/american-society-of-civil-engineers] Craven, Chief Engineer of the Croton Aqueduct and future ASCE president, the meeting resolved to incorporate the society under the name "American Society of Civil Engineers And Architects".
[src:construction/american-society-of-civil-engineers] The founding meeting was held on November 5, 1852, in the offices of the Croton Aqueduct Department at the Rotunda in City Hall Park, Manhattan.
[src:construction/american-society-of-civil-engineers] Membership eligibility was restricted to "civil, geological, mining and mechanical Engineers, architects, and other persons who, by profession, are interested in the advancement of science." James Laurie was elected the society's first president.
[src:construction/american-society-of-civil-engineers] At an early meeting of the Board of Direction in 1852, instructions were given for the incorporation of the "American Society of Civil Engineers and Architects" but this was the proper steps were never taken, and therefore this name never legally belonged to the association.
[src:construction/american-society-of-civil-engineers] The ASCE held its first meetings at the Croton Aqueduct Department building in City Hall Park.
[src:construction/american-society-of-civil-engineers] The meetings only went through 1855 and with the advent of the American Civil War, the society suspended its activities.
[src:construction/american-society-of-civil-engineers] The next meeting was more than twelve years later in 1867.
[src:construction/american-society-of-civil-engineers] A number of the original founders, such as James Laurie, J.W.
[src:construction/american-society-of-civil-engineers] Talcott, were at this meeting and were dedicated to the objective of resuscitating the society.
[src:construction/american-society-of-civil-engineers] They also planned to put the society on a more permanent footing and elect fifty-four new members.
[src:construction/american-society-of-civil-engineers] With success in that effort, the young engineering society passed a resolution noting that its preservation was mainly due to the persevering efforts of its first president, James Laurie.
[src:construction/american-society-of-civil-engineers] The address of President James Pugh Kirkwood delivered at that meeting in 1867 was the first publication of the society, appearing in Volume 1 of *Transactions*, bearing date of 1872.
[src:construction/american-society-of-civil-engineers] On March 4, 1868, by a vote of 17 to 4, the name was changed to "American Society of Civil Engineers", but it was not until April 17, 1877, that the lack of incorporation was discovered and the proper steps taken to remedy the defect.
[src:construction/american-society-of-civil-engineers] The society was then chartered and incorporated in New York state.
[src:construction/american-society-of-civil-engineers] The reconvened ASCE met at the Chamber of Commerce of the State of New York until 1875 when the society moved to 4 East 23rd Street.
[src:construction/american-society-of-civil-engineers] The ASCE moved again in 1877 to 104 East 20th Street and in 1881 to 127 East 23rd Street.
[src:construction/american-society-of-civil-engineers] The ASCE commissioned a new headquarters at 220 West 57th Street in 1895.
[src:construction/american-society-of-civil-engineers] The building was completed in 1897 and served as the society's headquarters until 1917 when the ASCE moved to the Engineering Societies' Building.
[src:construction/american-society-of-civil-engineers] Nora Stanton Barney was among the first women in the United States to earn a civil engineering degree, graduating from Cornell University in 1905.
[src:construction/american-society-of-civil-engineers] In the same year, she was accepted as a junior member of the organization and began work for the New York City Board of Water Supply.
[src:construction/american-society-of-civil-engineers] She was the first female member of ASCE, where she was allowed to be a junior member, but was denied advancement to associate member in 1916 because of her gender.
[src:construction/american-society-of-civil-engineers] In 2015, she was posthumously advanced to ASCE Fellow status.
[src:construction/american-society-of-civil-engineers] ASCE's headquarters relocated to the Engineering Societies' Building in 1917; additional floors were added on top of the building to accommodate the society's new offices.
[src:construction/american-society-of-civil-engineers] The weight of the extra stories could not be supported on the existing pilings, so four new steel columns were constructed through the structure, supported directly on the bedrock.
[src:construction/american-society-of-civil-engineers] In 1961, ASCE's headquarters moved from the Engineering Societies' Building to the United Engineering Center, a new skyscraper built for twenty different engineering societies across from the headquarters of the United Nations.
[src:construction/american-society-of-civil-engineers] In 1996, ASCE relocated its headquarters from New York City to Reston, Virginia.
[src:construction/american-society-of-civil-engineers] The relocation to the Washington metropolitan area was made to bring ASCE's headquarters closer to the legislative branch of the federal government and also reduced operating costs.
[src:construction/american-society-of-civil-engineers] In 1999, the ASCE elected the top-ten "civil engineering achievements that had the greatest positive impact on life in the 20th century" in "broad categories".
[src:construction/american-society-of-civil-engineers] Monuments of the Millennium were a "combination of technical engineering achievement, courage and inspiration, and a dramatic influence on the development of [their] communities".
[src:construction/american-society-of-civil-engineers] ASCE stated that dissemination of technical and professional information to the civil engineering profession was a major goal of the society.
[src:construction/american-society-of-civil-engineers] They also publish an online bibliographic database, conference proceedings, standards, manuals of practice, and technical reports.
[src:construction/american-society-of-civil-engineers] The ASCE Library contains 470+ e-books and standards, some with chapter-level access and no restrictive DRM, and 600+ online proceedings.
[src:construction/american-society-of-civil-engineers] Each year, more than 55,000 engineers earn continuing education units (CEUs) and/or professional development hours (PDHs) by participating in ASCE's continuing education programs.
[src:construction/american-society-of-civil-engineers] ASCE hosts more than 15 annual and specialty conferences, over 200 continuing education seminars and more than 300 live web seminars.
[src:construction/american-society-of-civil-engineers] Meetings include "...committees, task forces, focus groups, workshops and seminars designed to bring together civil engineering experts either from specific fields or those with a broad range of experience and skills.
[src:construction/american-society-of-civil-engineers] The engineering programs division directly advances the science of engineering by delivering technical content for ASCE's publications, conferences and continuing education programs.
[src:construction/american-society-of-civil-engineers] It consists of eight discipline-specific institutes, four technical divisions, and six technical councils.
[src:construction/american-society-of-civil-engineers] The work is accomplished by over 600 technical committees with editorial responsibility for 28 of ASCE's 33 journals.
[src:construction/american-society-of-civil-engineers] On an annual basis, the division conducts more than twelve congresses and specialty conferences.
[src:construction/american-society-of-civil-engineers] As a founding society of ANSI and accredited standards development organization, ASCE committees use an established and audited process to produce consensus standards under a program supervised by the society's Codes and Standards Committee.
[src:construction/american-society-of-civil-engineers] (CEC), affiliated with ASCE, has been established to support specialty certification academies for civil engineering specialties and is accredited by the Council of Engineering and Scientific Specialty Boards (CESB).
[src:construction/american-society-of-civil-engineers] CEC also handles safety certification for state, municipal, and federal buildings, formerly the province of the now-defunct Building Security Council.
[src:construction/american-society-of-civil-engineers] The Committee on Critical Infrastructure (CCI) provides vision and guidance on ASCE activities related to critical infrastructure resilience, including planning, design, construction, O&M, and event mitigation, response and recovery.
[src:construction/american-society-of-civil-engineers] Certification is the recognition of attaining advanced knowledge and skills in a specialty area of civil engineering.
[src:construction/american-society-of-civil-engineers] ASCE offers certifications for engineers who demonstrate advanced knowledge and skills in their area of engineering.
[src:construction/american-society-of-civil-engineers] Michel Award for Industry Advancement of Research and the Charles Pankow Award for innovation, 12 scholarships and fellowships for student members.
[src:construction/american-society-of-civil-engineers] Created in 1968 by ASCE's Sanitary Engineering Division, the Wesley W.
[src:construction/american-society-of-civil-engineers] Horner award is named after former ASCE President Wesley W.
[src:construction/american-society-of-civil-engineers] Horner, and given to a recently peer reviewed published paper in the fields of hydrology, urban drainage, or sewerage.
[src:construction/american-society-of-civil-engineers] Special consideration is given to private practice engineering work that is recognized as a valuable contribution to the field of environmental engineering.
[src:construction/american-society-of-civil-engineers] The Lifetime Achievement Award has been presented annually since 1999 and recognizes five different individual leaders.
[src:construction/american-society-of-civil-engineers] One award is present in each category of design, construction, government, education, and management.
[src:construction/american-society-of-civil-engineers] In July 1946, the Board of Direction authorized annual awards on recommendation by the society's Committee on Research to stimulate research in civil engineering.
[src:construction/american-society-of-civil-engineers] Alberta Reed Huber endowed these prizes in honor of her husband, Walter L.
[src:construction/american-society-of-civil-engineers] The Huber Prize is considered the highest level mid-career research prize in civil engineering and is awarded for outstanding achievements and contributions in research with respect to all disciplines of civil engineering.
[src:construction/american-society-of-civil-engineers] The LTPP International Data Analysis Contest is an annual data analysis contest held by the ASCE in collaboration with the Federal Highway Administration (FHWA).
[src:construction/american-society-of-civil-engineers] The participants utilize Long-Term Pavement Performance Program (LTPP) data as part of their analysis.
[src:construction/american-society-of-civil-engineers] At the instigation of the former students of Nathan Mortimore Newmark, the Nathan M.
[src:construction/american-society-of-civil-engineers] Newmark Medal was established in 1975 by the Engineering Mechanics Institute and Structural Engineering Institute of the American Society of Civil Engineers (ASCE) in honor of his contributions in structural engineering and mechanics.
[src:construction/american-society-of-civil-engineers] The medal is given to an ASCE member whose outstanding contributions in structural mechanics have substantially strengthened the scientific base of structural engineering, documented in the form of papers or other written presentations.
[src:construction/american-society-of-civil-engineers] Nominations are made once a year and due on November 1.
[src:construction/american-society-of-civil-engineers] The foundation board of directors has seven persons and its bylaws require that four of the seven directors must be ASCE officers as well and the ASCE executive director and chief financial officer must also be ASCE employees.
[src:construction/american-society-of-civil-engineers] The foundation's support is most often to ASCE's charitable, educational and scientific programs.
[src:construction/american-society-of-civil-engineers] The foundation's largest program is supporting three strategic areas; lifelong learning and leadership, advocacy for infrastructure investment and the role of civil engineers in sustainable practices.
[src:construction/american-society-of-civil-engineers] In 2014, this foundation's support in these areas was almost US$4 million.
[src:construction/american-society-of-civil-engineers] ASCE provides peer reviews at the request of public agencies and projects as a "means to improve the management and quality of [public agency] services and thus better protect the public health and safety with which they are entrusted".
[src:construction/american-society-of-civil-engineers] After the 2005 levee failures in Greater New Orleans, the commander of the U.S.
[src:construction/american-society-of-civil-engineers] Lawrence Roth, deputy executive director of the ASCE led the ERP development, served as the panel's chief of staff and facilitated its interaction with IPET.
[src:construction/american-society-of-civil-engineers] The expert panel's role was to provide an independent technical review of the IPET's activities and findings, as stated at a National Research Council meeting in New Orleans: "an independent review panel ensure[s] that the outcome is a robust, credible and defensible performance evaluation".
[src:construction/american-society-of-civil-engineers] Gen Strock gave all expert review panel members an Outstanding Civilian Service Medals.
[src:construction/american-society-of-civil-engineers] On June 1, 2007, the ASCE issued its expert review panel report, and an accompanying press release.
[src:construction/american-society-of-civil-engineers] The corps acknowledged receiving a copy of the letter and refused to comment until the ASCE's Committee on Professional Conduct (CPC) had commented on the complaint.
[src:construction/american-society-of-civil-engineers] It took over a year for the ASCE to announce the results of the CPC.
[src:construction/american-society-of-civil-engineers] On November 14, 2007, ASCE announced that U.S.
[src:construction/american-society-of-civil-engineers] (ret), would lead an independent task force of outside experts to review how ASCE participated in engineering studies of national significance.
[src:construction/american-society-of-civil-engineers] ASCE President David Mongan said the review was to address criticism of ASCE´s role in assisting the Army Corps of Engineers-sponsored investigation of Katrina failures.
[src:construction/american-society-of-civil-engineers] Mongan assured citizens of metro New Orleans in a letter to the *Times Picayune*, that ASCE took "this matter very seriously and that appropriate actions are being taken".
[src:construction/american-society-of-civil-engineers] The panel recommended in results released on September 12, 2008, that ASCE should immediately take steps to remove the potential for conflict of interest in its participation in post-disaster engineering studies.
[src:construction/american-society-of-civil-engineers] It concluded that ASCE should draw up an ethics policy to eliminate questions of possible conflicts of interest.
[src:construction/american-society-of-civil-engineers] On April 6, 2009, an internal probe with the ASCE issued a report that ordered a retraction of the ASCE's June 1, 2007, press release.
[src:construction/american-society-of-civil-engineers] On November 5, 2007, New Orleans–based grassroots group *Levees.org* led by Sandy Rosenthal criticized the ASCE's close relationship with the United States Army Corps of Engineers in a spoof online public service announcement.
[src:construction/american-society-of-civil-engineers] On November 12, 2007, the ASCE asked Levees.org to remove the video from the internet, threatening the organization with legal action if it did not comply.
[src:construction/american-society-of-civil-engineers] On November 13, the Times-Picayune posted the video on its website.
[src:construction/american-society-of-civil-engineers] In March 2008, Levees.org announced that records obtained under the Freedom of Information Act revealed that as early October 2005, the Army Corps of Engineers had directed and later paid the ASCE more than $1.1 million for its peer review (Grant Number: W912HZ-06-1-0001).
[src:construction/american-society-of-civil-engineers] The grant also paid for a series of misleading ASCE presentations attempting to shift blame away from the corps and onto local levee officials.
[src:construction/american-society-of-civil-engineers] Members of the ASCE are forbidden from making false or exaggerated statements and also from making statements for an interested party unless this is disclosed.
[src:construction/american-society-of-civil-engineers] Levees.org claimed the records showed how the external peer review would be done in four phases: Phase 1 was research and analysis on the performance of the levees, floodwalls and other important structures.
[src:construction/american-society-of-civil-engineers] Phase 2 was provision of information on the current system to prevent future flooding.
[src:construction/american-society-of-civil-engineers] Phase 3 was provision of information to evaluate alternative approaches to flood protection.
[src:construction/american-society-of-civil-engineers] Phase 4 was transfer information and knowledge gained to a broader audience within Corps and its consultancy community to communicate lessons learned.
[src:construction/american-society-of-civil-engineers] The group claimed that these records were proof that ASCE's routine powerpoint presentation from 2007 and 2008 were a public relations campaign to repair the corps' reputation.
[src:construction/american-society-of-civil-engineers] ASCE officials responded that ASCE paid for the powerpoint presentations itself and had not used USACE grant money for that purpose.
[src:construction/construction] The construction industry contributes significantly to many countries' gross domestic products (GDP).
[src:construction/construction] Global expenditure on construction activities was about $4 trillion in 2012.
[src:construction/construction] In 2022, expenditure on the construction industry exceeded $11 trillion a year, equivalent to about 13 percent of global GDP.
[src:construction/construction] This spending was forecasted to rise to around $14.8 trillion in 2030.
[src:construction/construction] The construction industry promotes economic development and brings many non-monetary benefits to many countries, but it is one of the most hazardous industries.
[src:construction/construction] For example, about 20% (1,061) of US industry fatalities in 2019 happened in construction.
[src:construction/construction] "Construction" stems from the Latin word *constructio* (which comes from *com-* "together" and *struere* "to pile up") as well as Old French *construction*.
[src:construction/construction] "To construct" is a verb: the act of building.
[src:construction/construction] The noun is "construction": how something is built or the nature of its structure.
[src:construction/construction] The first huts and shelters were constructed by hand or with simple tools.
[src:construction/construction] As cities grew during the Bronze Age, a class of professional craftsmen, like bricklayers and carpenters, appeared.
[src:construction/construction] Occasionally, slaves were used for construction work.
[src:construction/construction] In the Middle Ages, the artisan craftsmen were organized into craft guilds.
[src:construction/construction] In the 19th century, steam-powered machinery appeared, and later, diesel- and electric-powered vehicles such as cranes, excavators and bulldozers.
[src:construction/construction] Fast-track construction has been increasingly popular in the 21st century.
[src:construction/construction] Some estimates suggest that 40% of construction projects are now fast-track construction.
[src:construction/construction] The industry can also be classified into sectors or markets.
[src:construction/construction] For example, *Engineering News-Record* (*ENR*), a US-based construction trade magazine, has compiled and reported data about the size of design and construction contractors.
[src:construction/construction] In 2014, it split the data into nine market segments: transportation, petroleum, buildings, power, industrial, water, manufacturing, sewage/waste, telecom, hazardous waste, and a tenth category for other projects.
[src:construction/construction] *ENR* used data on transportation, sewage, hazardous waste and water to rank firms as heavy contractors.
[src:construction/construction] The Standard Industrial Classification and the newer North American Industry Classification System classify companies that perform or engage in construction into three subsectors: building construction, heavy and civil engineering construction, and specialty trade contractors.
[src:construction/construction] There are also categories for professional services firms (e.g., engineering, architecture, surveying, project management).
[src:construction/construction] Building construction is the process of adding structures to areas of land, also known as real property sites.
[src:construction/construction] Typically, a project is instigated by or with the owner of the property (who may be an individual or an organisation); occasionally, land may be compulsorily purchased from the owner for public use.
[src:construction/construction] Residential construction may be undertaken by individual land-owners (self-built), by specialist housebuilders, by property developers, by general contractors, or by providers of public or social housing (e.g.: local authorities, housing associations).
[src:construction/construction] Where local zoning or planning policies allow, mixed-use developments may comprise both residential and non-residential construction (e.g.: retail, leisure, offices, public buildings, etc.).
[src:construction/construction] Residential construction practices, technologies, and resources must conform to local building authority's regulations and codes of practice.
[src:construction/construction] Materials readily available in the area generally dictate the construction materials used (e.g.: brick versus stone versus timber).
[src:construction/construction] Costs of construction on a per square meter (or per square foot) basis for houses can vary dramatically based on site conditions, access routes, local regulations, economies of scale (custom-designed homes are often more expensive to build) and the availability of skilled tradespeople.
[src:construction/construction] Most construction in these sectors is undertaken by general contractors.
[src:construction/construction] Civil engineering covers the design, construction, and maintenance of the physical and naturally built environment, including public works such as roads, bridges, canals, dams, tunnels, airports, water and sewerage systems, pipelines, and railways.
[src:construction/construction] Some general contractors have expertise in civil engineering; civil engineering contractors are firms dedicated to work in this sector, and may specialise in particular types of infrastructure.
[src:construction/construction] Industrial construction includes offshore construction (mainly of energy installations: oil and gas platforms, wind power), mining and quarrying, refineries, food processing plants, breweries and distilleries, power stations, steel mills, warehouses and factories.
[src:construction/construction] Some construction projects are small renovations or repair jobs, like repainting or fixing leaks, where the owner may act as designer, paymaster and labourer for the entire project.
[src:construction/construction] However, more complex or ambitious projects usually require additional multi-disciplinary expertise and manpower, so the owner may commission one or more specialist businesses to undertake detailed planning, design, construction and handover of the work.
[src:construction/construction] Contracts are agreed for the delivery of services by all businesses, alongside other detailed plans aimed at ensuring legal, timely, on-budget and safe delivery of the specified works.
[src:construction/construction] Design, finance, and legal aspects overlap and interrelate.
[src:construction/construction] The design must be not only structurally sound and appropriate for the use and location, but must also be financially possible to build, and legal to use.
[src:construction/construction] The financial structure must be adequate to build the design provided and must pay amounts that are legally owed.
[src:construction/construction] Legal structures integrate design with other activities and enforce financial and other construction processes.
[src:construction/construction] These processes also affect procurement strategies.
[src:construction/construction] Some forms of procurement emphasize collaborative relationships (partnering, alliancing) between the client, the contractor, and other stakeholders within a construction project, seeking to ameliorate often highly competitive and adversarial industry practices.
[src:construction/construction] DfMA (design for manufacture and assembly) and so-called modern methods of construction approaches also emphasize early collaboration with manufacturers and suppliers regarding products and components.
[src:construction/construction] Construction or refurbishment work in a "live" environment (where residents or businesses remain living in or operating on the site) requires particular care, planning and communication.
[src:construction/construction] When applicable, a proposed construction project must comply with local land-use planning policies including zoning and building code requirements.
[src:construction/construction] Data may be gathered through site analysis, site surveys and geotechnical investigations.
[src:construction/construction] Construction normally cannot start until planning permission has been granted, and may require preparatory work to ensure relevant infrastructure has been upgraded before building work can commence.
[src:construction/construction] Preparatory works will also include surveys of existing utility lines to avoid damage-causing outages and other hazardous situations.
[src:construction/construction] Some legal requirements come from *malum in se* considerations, or the desire to prevent indisputably bad phenomena, e.g. explosions or bridge collapses.
[src:construction/construction] Other legal requirements come from *malum prohibitum* considerations, or factors that are a matter of custom or expectation, such as isolating businesses from a business district or residences from a residential district.
[src:construction/construction] During the construction of a building, a municipal building inspector usually inspects the ongoing work periodically to ensure that construction adheres to the approved plans and the local building code.
[src:construction/construction] Once construction is complete, any later changes made to a building or other asset that affect safety, including its use, expansion, structural integrity, and fire protection, usually require municipality approval.
[src:construction/construction] Depending on the type of project, mortgage bankers, accountants, and cost engineers may participate in creating an overall plan for the financial management of a construction project.
[src:construction/construction] The presence of the mortgage banker is highly likely, even in relatively small projects since the owner's equity in the property is the most obvious source of funding for a building project.
[src:construction/construction] Accountants act to study the expected monetary flow over the life of the project and to monitor the payouts throughout the process.
[src:construction/construction] Professionals including cost engineers, estimators and quantity surveyors apply expertise to relate the work and materials involved to a proper valuation.
[src:construction/construction] Financial planning ensures adequate safeguards and contingency plans are in place before the project is started, and ensures that the plan is properly executed over the life of the project.
[src:construction/construction] Construction projects can suffer from preventable financial problems.
[src:construction/construction] Underbids happen when builders ask for too little money to complete the project.
[src:construction/construction] Cash flow problems exist when the present amount of funding cannot cover the current costs for labour and materials; such problems may arise even when the overall budget is adequate, presenting a temporary issue.
[src:construction/construction] Cost overruns with government projects have occurred when the contractor identified change orders or project changes that increased costs, which are not subject to competition from other firms as they have already been eliminated from consideration after the initial bid.
[src:construction/construction] Fraud is also an issue of growing significance within construction.
[src:construction/construction] Large projects can involve highly complex financial plans and often start with a conceptual cost estimate performed by a building estimator.
[src:construction/construction] As portions of a project are completed, they may be sold, supplanting one lender or owner for another, while the logistical requirements of having the right trades and materials available for each stage of the building construction project carry forward.
[src:construction/construction] Public–private partnerships (PPPs) or private finance initiatives (PFIs) may also be used to help deliver major projects.
[src:construction/construction] According to McKinsey in 2019, the "vast majority of large construction projects go over budget and take 20% longer than expected".
[src:construction/construction] Law related to construction primarily focuses around contracts and obligations, as well as planning permissions and legal matters on topics such as infrastructure, housing, engineering, insurance, the environment and building warrants.
[src:construction/construction] A construction project is a complex net of construction contracts and other legal obligations, each of which all parties must carefully consider.
[src:construction/construction] A contract is the exchange of a set of obligations between two or more parties, and provides structures to manage issues.
[src:construction/construction] For example, construction delays can be costly, so construction contracts set out clear expectations and clear paths to manage delays.
[src:construction/construction] Poorly drafted contracts can lead to confusion and costly disputes.
[src:construction/construction] At the start of a project, legal advisors seek to identify ambiguities and other potential sources of trouble in the contract structures, and to present options for preventing problems.
[src:construction/construction] During projects, they work to avoid and resolve conflicts that arise and processes such as negotiation and arbitration may take place.
[src:construction/construction] Design-bid-build is the most common and well-established method of construction procurement.
[src:construction/construction] In this arrangement, the architect, engineer or builder acts for the client as the project coordinator.
[src:construction/construction] They design the works, prepare specifications and design deliverables (models, drawings, etc.), administer the contract, tender the works, and manage the works from inception to completion.
[src:construction/construction] In parallel, there are direct contractual links between the client and the main contractor, who, in turn, has direct contractual relationships with subcontractors.
[src:construction/construction] The arrangement continues until the project is ready for handover.
[src:construction/construction] Design-build became more common from the late 20th century, and involves the client contracting a single entity to provide design and construction.
[src:construction/construction] In some cases, the design-build package can also include finding the site, arranging funding and applying for all necessary statutory consents.
[src:construction/construction] Typically, the client invites several Design & Build (D&B) contractors to submit proposals to meet the project brief and then selects a preferred supplier.
[src:construction/construction] Often this will be a consortium involving a design firm and a contractor (sometimes more than one of each).
[src:construction/construction] In the United States, departments of transportation usually use design-build contracts as a way of progressing projects where states lack the skills or resources, particularly for very large projects.
[src:construction/construction] In a construction management arrangement, the client enters into separate contracts with the designer (architect or engineer), a construction manager, and individual trade contractors.
[src:construction/construction] The client takes on the contractual role, while the construction or project manager provides the active role of managing the separate trade contracts, and ensuring that they complete all work smoothly and effectively together.
[src:construction/construction] In the industrialized world, construction usually involves the translation of designs into reality.
[src:construction/construction] Most commonly (i.e.: in a design-bid-build project), the design team is employed by (i.e. in contract with) the property owner.
[src:construction/construction] Depending upon the type of project, a design team may include architects, civil engineers, mechanical engineers, electrical engineers, structural engineers, fire protection engineers, planning consultants, architectural consultants, and archaeological consultants.
[src:construction/construction] A 'lead designer' will normally be identified to help coordinate different disciplinary inputs to the overall design.
[src:construction/construction] This may be aided by integration of previously separate disciplines (often undertaken by separate firms) into multi-disciplinary firms with experts from all related fields, or by firms establishing relationships to support design-build processes.
[src:construction/construction] For buildings, building engineering is an emerging discipline that attempts to meet this new challenge.
[src:construction/construction] Traditionally, design has involved the production of sketches, architectural and engineering drawings, and specifications.
[src:construction/construction] Some projects may include elements that are designed for off-site construction (see also DfMA, prefabrication and modular building) and are then delivered to the site ready for erection, installation or assembly.
[src:construction/construction] Once contractors and other relevant professionals have been appointed and designs are sufficiently advanced, work may commence on the project site.
[src:construction/construction] Some projects require preliminary works, such as land preparation and levelling, demolition of existing structures (see below), or laying foundations, and there are circumstances where this work may be contracted for in advance of finalising the contract and costs for the whole project.
[src:construction/construction] Typically, a construction site will include a secure perimeter to restrict unauthorised access, site access control points, office and welfare accommodation for personnel from the main contractor and other firms involved in the project team, and storage areas for materials, machinery and equipment.
[src:construction/construction] According to the *McGraw-Hill Dictionary of Architecture and Construction's* definition, construction may be said to have *started* when the first feature of the permanent structure has been put in place, such as pile driving, or the pouring of slabs or footings.
[src:construction/construction] Commissioning is the process of verifying that all subsystems of a new building (or other assets) work as intended to achieve the owner's project requirements and as designed by the project's architects and engineers.
[src:construction/construction] A period after handover (or practical completion) during which the owner may identify any shortcomings in relation to the building specification ('defects'), with a view to the contractor correcting the defect.
[src:construction/construction] Maintenance involves functional checks, servicing, repairing or replacing of necessary devices, equipment, machinery, building infrastructure, and supporting utilities in industrial, business, governmental, and residential installations.
[src:construction/construction] Demolition is the discipline of safely and efficiently tearing down buildings and other artificial structures.
[src:construction/construction] Demolition contrasts with deconstruction, which involves taking a building apart while carefully preserving valuable elements for reuse purposes (recycling – see also circular economy).
[src:construction/construction] The output of the global construction industry was worth an estimated $10.8 trillion in 2017, and in 2018 was forecast to rise to $12.9 trillion by 2022, and to around $14.8 trillion in 2030.
[src:construction/construction] As a sector, construction accounts for more than 10% of global GDP (in developed countries, construction comprises 6–9% of GDP), and employs around 7% of the total employed workforce around the globe (accounting for over 273 million full- and part-time jobs in 2014).
[src:construction/construction] Since 2010, China has been the world's largest single construction market.
[src:construction/construction] The United States is the second largest construction market with a 2018 output of $1.581 trillion.
[src:construction/construction] Construction is a major source of employment in most countries; high reliance on small businesses, and under-representation of women are common traits.
[src:construction/construction] According to McKinsey research, productivity growth per worker in construction has lagged behind many other industries across different countries including in the United States and in European countries.
[src:construction/construction] In the United States, construction productivity per worker has declined by half since the 1960s.
[src:construction/construction] Some workers may be engaged in manual labour as unskilled or semi-skilled workers; they may be skilled tradespeople; or they may be supervisory or managerial personnel.
[src:construction/construction] Laborers comprise a large grouping in most national construction industries.
[src:construction/construction] In the United States, for example, in May 2023, the construction sector employed just over 7.9 million people, of whom 859,000 were laborers, while 3.7 million were construction trades workers (including 603,000 carpenters, 559,000 electricians, 385,000 plumbers, and 321,000 equipment operators).
[src:construction/construction] Large-scale construction requires collaboration across multiple disciplines.
[src:construction/construction] A project manager normally manages the budget on the job, and a construction manager, design engineer, construction engineer or architect supervises it.
[src:construction/construction] Some models and policy-making organisations promote the engagement of local labour in construction projects as a means of tackling social exclusion and addressing skill shortages.
[src:construction/construction] In the UK, the Joseph Rowntree Foundation reported in 2000 on 25 projects which had aimed to offer training and employment opportunities for locally based school leavers and unemployed people.
[src:construction/construction] The Foundation published "a good practice resource book" in this regard at the same time.
[src:construction/construction] Use of local labour and local materials were specified for the construction of the Danish Storebaelt bridge, but there were legal issues which were challenged in court and addressed by the European Court of Justice in 1993.
[src:construction/construction] The court held that a contract condition requiring use of local labour and local materials was incompatible with EU treaty principles.
[src:construction/construction] Later UK guidance noted that social and employment clauses, where used, must be compatible with relevant EU regulation.
[src:construction/construction] There are many routes to the different careers within the construction industry.
[src:construction/construction] Unskilled and semi-skilled workers provide general site labor, often have few or no construction qualifications, and may receive basic site training.
[src:construction/construction] Skilled tradespeople have typically served apprenticeships (sometimes in labor unions) or received technical training; this group also includes on-site managers who possess extensive knowledge and experience in their craft or profession.
[src:construction/construction] Skilled manual occupations include carpenters, electricians, plumbers, ironworkers, heavy equipment operators and masons, as well as those involved in project management.
[src:construction/construction] In the UK these require further education qualifications, often in vocational subject areas, undertaken either directly after completing compulsory education or through "on the job" apprenticeships.
[src:construction/construction] Professional, technical and managerial personnel often have higher education qualifications, usually graduate degrees, and are trained to design and manage construction processes.
[src:construction/construction] These roles require more training as they demand greater technical knowledge, and involve more legal responsibility.
[src:construction/construction] Construction is one of the most dangerous occupations in the world, incurring more occupational fatalities than any other sector in both the United States and in the European Union.
[src:construction/construction] In the US in 2019, 1,061, or about 20%, of worker fatalities in private industry occurred in construction.
[src:construction/construction] In 2017, more than a third of US construction fatalities (366 out of 971 total fatalities) were the result of falls; in the UK, half of the average 36 fatalities per annum over a five-year period to 2021 were attributed to falls from height.
[src:construction/construction] Proper safety equipment such as harnesses, hard hats and guardrails and procedures such as securing ladders and inspecting scaffolding can curtail the risk of occupational injuries in the construction industry.
[src:construction/construction] Other major causes of fatalities in the construction industry include electrocution, transportation accidents, and trench cave-ins.
[src:construction/construction] Other safety risks for workers in construction include hearing loss due to high noise exposure, musculoskeletal injury, chemical exposure, and high levels of stress.
[src:construction/construction] Besides that, the high turnover of workers in construction industry imposes a huge challenge of accomplishing the restructuring of work practices in individual workplaces or with individual workers.
[src:construction/construction] Construction has been identified by the National Institute for Occupational Safety and Health (NIOSH) as a priority industry sector in the National Occupational Research Agenda (NORA) to identify and provide intervention strategies regarding occupational health and safety issues.
[src:construction/construction] A study conducted in 2022 found "significant effect of air pollution exposure on construction-related injuries and fatalities", especially with the exposure of nitrogen dioxide.
[src:construction/construction] The construction industry may require transformation at pace and at scale if it is to successfully contribute to achieving the target set out in The Paris Agreement of limiting global temperature rise to 1.5C above industrial levels.
[src:construction/construction] The World Green Building Council has stated the buildings and infrastructure around the world can reach 40% less embodied carbon emissions but that this can only be achieved through urgent transformation.
[src:construction/construction] Conclusions from industry leaders have suggested that the net zero transformation is likely to be challenging for the construction industry, but it does present an opportunity.
[src:construction/construction] Action is demanded from governments, standards bodies, the construction sector, and the engineering profession to meet the decarbonising targets.
[src:construction/construction] In 2021, the National Engineering Policy Centre published its report *Decarbonising Construction: Building a new net zero industry,* which outlined key areas to decarbonise the construction sector and the wider built environment.
[src:construction/construction] Progress is being made internationally to decarbonise the sector including improvements to sustainable procurement practice such as the CO2 performance ladder in the Netherlands and the Danish Partnership for Green Public Procurement.
[src:construction/construction] There are also now demonstrations of applying the principles of circular economy practices in practice such as Circl, ABN AMRO's sustainable pavilion and the Brighton Waste House.
